<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-237-018 </DOCNO><DOCID>09 407 074</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Jan 28 1991 n336 p47(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fighting the ATandamp;T card; card companies eyeing telecom business.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rocks, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The successful introduction of ATandamp;T's combination creditcard-calling card has prompted competing long distance carriersand card issuers to band together and fight back.andP;  ATandamp;T has opened4.1 million accounts since the card's introduction in Mar 1990,making it the fifth-largest issuer of bank credit cards.andP;  Creditcard companies view the long distance market as a profitable newmarket.andP;  Long distance carriers see alliances with credit cardissuers as a way to provide added convenience for their customers.andO;Visa International now offers the Visaphone service; AmericanExpress offers a choice between MCI and US Sprint for US calls;Diners Club offers MCI services.andP;  US domestic credit cardcompanies are also looking for new partners abroad.andP;  Credit cardswould have to be compatible with card-operated pay phones inforeign countries.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CreditLong-Distance Telephone ServicesTelephone CompaniesTelecommunications ServicesCommunications Service SuppliersCompetitionMarket Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>